{"id":"1204.2463","submitter":"Bala Sundaram","authors":"Timothy Killingback, Gregory Loftus and Bala Sundaram","title":"Competitively Coupled Maps and Spatial Pattern Formation","comments":"8 pages, 7 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.87.022902","report-no":null,"categories":"nlin.PS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Spatial pattern formation is a key feature of many natural systems in\nphysics, chemistry and biology. The essential theoretical issue in\nunderstanding pattern formation is to explain how a spatially homogeneous\ninitial state can undergo spontaneous symmetry breaking leading to a stable\nspatial pattern. This problem is most commonly studied using partial\ndifferential equations to model a reaction-diffusion system of the type\nintroduced by Turing. We report here on a much simpler and more robust model of\nspatial pattern formation, which is formulated as a novel type of coupled map\nlattice. In our model, the local site dynamics are coupled through a\ncompetitive, rather than diffusive, interaction. Depending only on the strength\nof the interaction, this competitive coupling results in spontaneous symmetry\nbreaking of a homogeneous initial configuration and the formation of stable\nspatial patterns. This mechanism is very robust and produces stable pattern\nformation for a wide variety of spatial geometries, even when the local site\ndynamics is trivial.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 11 Apr 2012 14:40:21 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 25 Jan 2013 14:00:44 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-04"}
